Women & the American Story (WAMS) is a free curriculum website from the New-York Historical Society. WAMS connects educators with classroom resources that illuminate diverse women’s contributions to the American past.

Explore the Units

1492–1734 Early Encounters 1692-1783 Settler Colonialism and the Revolution 1776-1831 Building a New Nation 1820-1869 Expansions and Inequalities 1832-1877 A Nation Divided 1866–1904 Industry and Empire 1889–1920 Modernizing America 1920–1948 Confidence and Crises 1948–1977 Growth and Turmoil 1977-2001 End of the Twentieth Century

Browse Highlights

Early Encounters, 1492-1734

Daughters of the King

The Filles du Roi moved to New France to marry eligible colonists in exchange for free passage and a small dowry.

View

Industry and Empire, 1866-1904

Edmonia Lewis: Sculptor and Activist

Edmonia Lewis was a Black and Indigenous sculptor who built a successful career through activist art.

View

Building a New Nation, 1776-1831

Women’s Suffrage Experiment

In 1776, New Jersey granted the right to vote to any person who lived in the state and owned property worth at least 50 pounds.

View

Confidence and Crises, 1920-1948

Anna May Wong: Movie Star

Anna May Wong achieved international fame as a film actor despite racism and stereotyping.

View

Growth and Turmoil, 1948-1977

An Educator Organizes for the Puerto Rican Community

Antonia Pantoja was an educator and social worker who advanced educational opportunities for New York’s Puerto Rican community.

View

Settler Colonialism and the American Revolution, 1692-1783

Fashionable Rebellion

Free Black women in Spanish Louisiana turned an oppressive law into a celebration of individuality and culture.

View

Modernizing America, 1889-1920

Fighting for the Rights of Native People

Zitkala-Sa was an activist and composer who fought tirelessly for Native American rights and citizenship.

View

A Nation Divided, 1832-1877

An Abolitionist and Women’s Rights Advocate Fights for Social Justice

Sojourner Truth took her freedom in 1828 and became a vocal fighter for abolition and women’s rights, traveling the country to share her story.

View

Building a New Nation, 1776-1831

Early American Consumers

American women purchased goods to support the U.S. economy in its early years. Household items could signal that a woman was up on the latest fashions and supported American trade efforts abroad.

View

Settler Colonialism and the American Revolution, 1692-1783

Colonial Pennsylvanian Scientist

Susanna Wright was a Quaker scientist, poet, and innovator who became the first person to successfully cultivate silk worms in Pennsylvania.

View

Industry and Empire, 1866-1904

Idaho Pioneer

Polly Bemis was a Chinese immigrant who became a pioneer in Idaho.

View

Growth and Turmoil, 1948-1977

Strike for Equality

On August 26, 1970, the women of America went on strike. In New York City, an estimated 50,000 women participated in a march down Fifth Avenue.

View

Modernizing America, 1889-1920

Mexican Women Unionize

In 1919, laundry workers in El Paso, Texas, formed a union and fought against unfair labor practices.

View

Confidence and Crises, 1920-1948

Integrated Defense Industry

Black women looked to jobs in the defense industry during World War II to provide higher wages and more regulated hours.

View

Video Library

Bring WAMS to life using short animated videos based on inspiring women’s stories and key themes. Find more in the Video Library.

New Netherland, How Two New Amsterdam Women Prevented a Colonial War

Learn about Lydia de Meyer and Hillegond van Ruyven, two women who opened negotiations with English invaders in 1664 to facilitate the surrender of New Netherland.

Watch (2:17)

Chien-Shiung Wu, Physicist and Manhattan Project Contributor

Learn more about Chien-Shiung Wu, a Chinese American physicist who contributed to the development of the atomic bomb and overcame many racial and gender barriers.

Watch (2:29)

Mary Church Terrell, Championing Suffrage and Civil Rights

Learn more about Mary Church Terrell, a lifelong activist who advocated for suffrage and equal rights on local, national, and international stages.

Watch (2:06)
